@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@
+# Codex Writer Findings — StaffOrdersMobile
+Chain: staffordersmobile-260415-161942-d5a3
+
+## Findings
+1. [P1] Closed finish-stage orders are still filtered out before grouping — In `pages/StaffOrdersMobile/260414-02 StaffOrdersMobile RELEASE.jsx:3577-3584`, the finish-stage branch still returns `o.status !== 'closed' && o.status !== 'cancelled'`. That removes fully closed orders before they reach `visibleOrders` and `orderGroups`, so the "Completed" tab cannot render a just-closed table. FIX: change the finish-stage filter to exclude only `cancelled`, while keeping the existing shift-cutoff guard for historical data.
+2. [P1] Close-table flow still leaves request state active — `components/sessionHelpers.js:158-169` closes the `TableSession` and orders only; it never completes open `ServiceRequest` rows for the table. Then `pages/StaffOrdersMobile/260414-02 StaffOrdersMobile RELEASE.jsx:4148-4152` refetches only orders, so `activeRequests` can continue to satisfy `hasActiveRequest` in `filteredGroups` and keep the table out of "Completed" until a later poll. FIX: after closing the session orders, also close open `ServiceRequest`s for that table, and refetch or invalidate `["serviceRequests"]` after `closeSession(sessionId)` for non-kitchen users.
+3. [P0] `closeSession()` still uses parallel order updates — In `components/sessionHelpers.js:163-167`, the order-closing path uses `Promise.all(...)` over every non-cancelled order in the session. A table with several orders will still burst multiple Base44 `Order.update` calls at once and can reproduce the reported 429 rate-limit failure. FIX: replace the `Promise.all` block with a sequential loop and a 120ms delay between updates.
+4. [P1] Collapsed-card bulk request actions still fan out parallel mutations — The collapsed hall-card bulk buttons at `pages/StaffOrdersMobile/260414-02 StaffOrdersMobile RELEASE.jsx:657` and `:1272` still use `tableRequests.forEach(...)` with `onCloseRequest(...)`. That fires one mutation per request immediately, along with one invalidate per mutation through `updateRequestMutation`, which keeps the rate-limit hole open in collapsed mode even though the expanded card already uses `runBatchSequential(...)`. FIX: switch both collapsed bulk handlers to the same `runBatchSequential(...)` + `onBatchCloseRequestAsync(...)` pattern used at `:2369`, then invalidate `["serviceRequests"]` once after the batch.
+5. [P1] Fix 1 does not fully cover the reopened-table acceptance case — `orderGroups` in `pages/StaffOrdersMobile/260414-02 StaffOrdersMobile RELEASE.jsx:3743-3757` groups hall orders only by `tableId`. If closed orders from the old session are allowed through and a new session is opened on the same table before shift cutoff, both sessions collapse into one table group, which contradicts verification step 7 ("separate orderGroup — different session"). FIX: make hall grouping session-aware for completed-session data, or otherwise split old closed-session orders from the current open session before building table groups.
+6. [P3] `updateStatusMutation` is missing the existing batch guard pattern — In `pages/StaffOrdersMobile/260414-02 StaffOrdersMobile RELEASE.jsx:1594-1606`, `updateStatusMutation.onSettled` always invalidates `["orders"]`, unlike `advanceMutation` at `:1916-1919`. I did not find a current batched caller of `updateStatusMutation` in this file, so this is a consistency/prevention issue rather than a reproduced user-visible regression. FIX: align `onSettled` with `advanceMutation` and skip invalidation when `vars?.__batch` is set.
+
+## Summary
+Total: 6 findings (1 P0, 4 P1, 0 P2, 1 P3)
+
+## Prompt Clarity (MANDATORY — do NOT skip this section)
+- Overall clarity: 4
+- Ambiguous Fix descriptions (list Fix # and what was unclear): Fix 1b assumes `getLinkId(...)` is available inside `components/sessionHelpers.js`, but that helper is not currently defined or imported there. Fix 4 describes a consistency change, but this version does not contain a batched caller of `updateStatusMutation`, so its current repro path is not explicit.
+- Missing context (what info would have helped): The task expects reopened tables to appear as separate old/new groups, but the current grouping code is table-based. A note on the intended grouping key for closed historical sessions would remove that ambiguity.
+- Scope questions (anything you weren't sure if it's in scope): The session-grouping gap for reopened tables is logically part of Fix 1 verification, but its code lives outside the listed edit lines. I treated it as in scope because the stated acceptance criteria depend on it.
